{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569874"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22426"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22426"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.44,0.43,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109565"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15390"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91942"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2934"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"9084"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40998"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109565"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of generalised itching and his urine becoming darker in colour. His medical history includes a distal gastrectomy for a signet ring cell carcinoma, performed two years ago. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 116/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is obviously jaundiced. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum bilirubin 86 \u00b5mol/L (2-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT 320 U/L (\u0026lt;51)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST 230 U/L (\u0026lt;51)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis: +++ bilirubin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan is performed (Images 1-2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange outpatient gastroenterology review","Order magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography","Request consult from hepatobiliary surgery","Commence ursodeoxycholic acid","Commence amoxicillin, gentamicin, metronidazole IV"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with obstructive jaundice, likely due to metastatic gastric cancer given his history of signet ring cell carcinoma. The CT scan shows a dilated common bile duct and dilated intrahepatic ducts, with extrinsic compression of the lower end of the common bile duct by a mass lesion (identified by the arrow). The arrow points to the source of his current problem (Image 3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe biliary obstruction combined with his history of malignancy and significantly deranged liver function tests, warrants urgent inpatient management. \u003Cstrong\u003ERequest consult from hepatobiliary surgery\u003C/strong\u003E is most appropriate to expedite specialist review and intervention. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging outpatient gastroenterology review\u003C/strong\u003E would delay necessary urgent intervention. The degree of jaundice and likelihood of malignant obstruction makes outpatient management inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography \u003C/strong\u003E(MRCP) as an outpatient would delay definitive management. While this imaging may eventually be required, it should be arranged by the treating team after admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing ursodeoxycholic acid\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying mechanical obstruction and would inappropriately delay definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence amoxicillin, gentamicin, metronidazole IV\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for ascending cholangitis, but this patient lacks the typical features (fever, right upper quadrant pain, shock) that would suggest this diagnosis. The patient requires admission for comprehensive assessment, planning, and likely urgent biliary decompression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key learning point is that suspected malignant biliary obstruction requires urgent inpatient management. The treating team can then coordinate appropriate imaging, specialist review, and intervention in a timely manner.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obstructive jaundice requires urgent specialist referral for investigation and management.","Initial investigations for obstructive jaundice should include liver function tests, coagulation profile, and CT imaging.","Patients with suspected malignant biliary obstruction require urgent referral to hepatobiliary surgery."],"references":["Wang Y, Wen N, Xiong X. Biliary drainage in malignant biliary obstruction: an umbrella review of randomized controlled trials. Front Oncol. 2023 Sep 5:13:1235490. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37731638/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91942"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22426"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21064"},{"type":"media","id":"21065"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21963"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21064"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/r4jcCylTRj5cIZVKYm4kDi6BK7eVHh.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/r4jcCylTRj5cIZVKYm4kDi6BK7eVHh.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":806,"height":670}},{"type":"media","id":"21065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21065"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c2dUWvROKl81lKzHSXJ33r6qaxCff6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c2dUWvROKl81lKzHSXJ33r6qaxCff6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":613,"height":761}},{"type":"media","id":"21963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21963"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jzDaqjwfhb1bVVoArFmURdyOZrlVj4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jzDaqjwfhb1bVVoArFmURdyOZrlVj4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":613,"height":761}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91942"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-22T16:20:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-22T16:28:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15390"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109565"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description"